<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920207-0042</DOCNO><DOCID>920207-0042.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Fleming Cos.:   Fourth-Quarter Net Loss   Of $21.6 Million Is Posted</HL><DATE>02/07/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   FLM</CO><MS>CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)FOOD RETAILERS AND WHOLESALERS, CONVENIENCE STORES (FDR)</IN><NS>EARNINGS (ERN)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)OKLAHOMA (OK)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Fleming Cos. said it had a net loss of $21.6 million, or63 cents a share, for the fourth quarter, including more than$50 million in after-tax charges.   The Oklahoma City-based wholesale food distributor said ittook a $67 million charge, or $41.4 million after tax, forcosts related to closing and consolidating some of its 36distribution centers nationwide. Fleming said theconsolidation, which will reduce its work force by 1,000 overtwo years, should increase its efficiency.</LP><TEXT>   In the fourth quarter of 1990, Fleming had net income of$26.7 million, or 84 cents a share. Revenue for the periodrose 5.1% to $3.08 billion from $2.93 billion.   The company didn't specify how many centers will be closedbut said it hopes to move toward larger, higher-volumedistribution centers such as &quot;super centers&quot; handling $700million to $1 billion of wholesale sales a year.   The fourth-quarter results also include a $9.3 millioncharge related to a change in accounting for retirees'medical benefits.   The net loss was the company's first deficit since thefirst quarter of 1986, when it also recorded a charge from anaccounting change. Without the charges, Fleming said it wouldhave had profit of $29 million, or 77 cents a share. Thecompany had 35.4 million weighted average shares outstandingin the latest quarter, up from 30.5 million a year before.</TEXT></DOC>